issue.title: [sdk] Types for kfp and kfp.dsl are not found by mypy
issue.body:
### Environment


All dependencies version:

* kfp 1.8.12 and 1.8.18
* mypy 1.0.0

I am managing my dependencies with poetry.  

### Steps to reproduce

```
import kfp.dsl as dsl
```

Run `mypy` 

Produces error:

```
file.py:1: error: Skipping analyzing "kfp.dsl": module is installed, but missing library stubs or py.typed marker  [import]
```

### Expected result

Type stubs are included in project.  

### Materials and Reference

It looks like this issue was addressed in #7451 but it doesn't seem to work for me.  

---

issue.title: [sdk] AIP_STORAGE_URI is not correctly set up, when importing a custom trained model to ModelBatchPredictOp
issue.body:
### Environment

*  All dependencies version:
kfp ==  1.8.22
google-cloud-pipeline-components == 1.0.45

### Steps to reproduce

- I am training the model with custom container, using the CustomTrainingJobOp;
- Afterwards, I am uploading model to model registry, using custom upload component (code below), because I want to to have the parent-child model relationships saved, and with standard ModelUploadOp it is not working ([known issue](https://github.com/kubeflow/pipelines/issues/8881));  I specify env variable AIP_STORAGE_URI  explicitly, and if we check uploaded model, we can see it being added in UI:

![model_registry](https://github.com/kubeflow/pipelines/assets/43318715/b138fce1-2ba0-4461-8430-2f8860dd703c)

- then, in order to use model in ModelBatchPredictOp, I am first getting the model with GetVertexModelOp, and then use the model in batch prediction job, as expected;


```python
get_model_for_inf_task = GetVertexModelOp(
    model_resource_name=parent_model_res_name
).set_display_name("Get model for inference")

batch_prediction_task = (
    ModelBatchPredictOp(
        project=PROJECT_ID,
        model=get_model_for_inf_task.outputs["model"],
        location=REGION,
        job_display_name="Batch_prediction_custom_model_INFERENCE",
        gcs_source_uris=[
            f"{MODEL_DIR}/df_output.jsonl"
        ],  
        instances_format="jsonl",
        predictions_format="jsonl",
        gcs_destination_output_uri_prefix=parent_model_uri,
        machine_type="n1-standard-32",
        manual_batch_tuning_parameters_batch_size=create_jsonl_batch_task.outputs[
            "batch_size"
        ],  
    )
    .set_display_name("Batch prediction custom model (INFERENCE)")
    .set_cpu_limit("32")
    .set_memory_limit("512G")
)

```

- ModelBatchPredictOp uses the custom serving image for my model; in this custom serving image I use AIP_STORAGE_URI  to construct the path to model.joblib and some additional artifacts needed for predictions; 
- **The problem** : when prediction job  is running, instead of using AIP_STORAGE_URI   specified when uploading model, it is somehow uses the "standard" AIP_STORAGE_URI, that looks like this: 

`gs://caip-tenant-68ba344c-c628-448d-ba39-255e1644e515/model_artifacts/artifacts`

- **The problem does not reproduce, if** instead of GetVertexModelOp I use `importer_node.importer` (code below)

in this case the AIP_STORAGE_URI  looks like this: 

`gs://caip-tenant-c328126f-3e28-4823-a147-3eca3c390550/model_artifacts/02254579/pipeline_root_add_card-v1_oct_2023_20231024153409/MODEL_ROOT_add_card-v1_oct_2023/model/add_card-v1_oct_2023`

from which I can re-construct the "original" AIP_STORAGE_URI  like this:

```
aip_storage_uri = (
    GCP_SAVE_DIR + "/" + AIP_STORAGE_URI.split("model_artifacts/")[1]
)
```
and the code for the importer and batch predictions:

```python
import_unmanaged_model_inf_task = importer_node.importer(
    artifact_uri=parent_model_uri,
    artifact_class=artifact_types.UnmanagedContainerModel,
    metadata={
        "containerSpec": {
            "imageUri": serving_image,
            "healthRoute": "/health_check",
            "predictRoute": "/predict",
        },
    },
).set_display_name("Get model for predictions")


batch_prediction_task = (
                    ModelBatchPredictOp(
                        project=PROJECT_ID,
                        unmanaged_container_model=import_unmanaged_model_inf_task.outputs[
                            "artifact"
                        ],
                        location=REGION,
                        job_display_name="Batch_prediction_custom_model_INFERENCE",
                        gcs_source_uris=[
                            f"{MODEL_DIR}/df_output.jsonl"
                        ],  
                        instances_format="jsonl",
                        predictions_format="jsonl",
                        gcs_destination_output_uri_prefix=parent_model_uri,
                        machine_type="n1-standard-32",
                        manual_batch_tuning_parameters_batch_size=create_jsonl_batch_task.outputs[
                            "batch_size"
                        ],  
                    )
                    .set_display_name("Batch prediction custom model (INFERENCE)")
                    .set_cpu_limit("32")
                    .set_memory_limit("512G")
                    .after(create_jsonl_batch_task)
                )
```
- why overall this is a problem, why not just use importer_node.importer ? because when using importer, in batch predict job we then have the link to "unmanaged" container, and not to the model, as we will have when use GetVertexModelOp, check screenshots:

when using GetVertexModelOp, in batch predictions UI:
![batch_pred_getvertex](https://github.com/kubeflow/pipelines/assets/43318715/b4ce5914-d2fe-4e93-b10a-58f5f55711bf)
![batch_pred_getvertex_2](https://github.com/kubeflow/pipelines/assets/43318715/48653ba1-9983-4cec-b831-65be385340c0)

when using importer, in batch predictions UI:
![batch_pred_importer](https://github.com/kubeflow/pipelines/assets/43318715/7aa50573-50d7-4193-8f3f-6689cbcc92b2)
![batch_pred_importer_2](https://github.com/kubeflow/pipelines/assets/43318715/dbec89d5-1c3d-40b3-8156-257aeed7d50e)



### Expected result

The env variable AIP_STORAGE_URI should be the same if using both importer_node.importer and GetVertexModelOp 

### Materials and Reference
custom model_upload component: 
```python
from kfp.v2.dsl import Artifact, Dataset, Input, Model, Output, Metrics, component
from datallience_pipelines import BASE_IMAGE, TEMPLATES_SAVE_FOLDER
from typing import NamedTuple


@component(
    base_image=BASE_IMAGE,
    output_component_file=f"{TEMPLATES_SAVE_FOLDER}/upload_model.yaml",
    # packages_to_install=["google-cloud-aiplatform", "google-cloud-pipeline-components"],
)
def upload_model(
    MODEL_DIR: str,
    CURRENT_ENV: str,
    display_name: str,
    model_display_name: str,
    serving_container_image_uri: str,
    project_location: str,
    project_id: str,
    labels: dict,
    description: str = None,
    sync: bool = True,
    parent_model_id: int = 0,
    version_aliases: list = ["experimental"],
    parent_model_uri: str = None,
    parent_model_res_name: str = None,
    aip_storage_uri: str = None,
    serving_env: dict = None,
) -> NamedTuple("Outputs", [("model_resource_name", str)]):
    import os
    import google.cloud.logging

            serving_container_health_route="/health_check",  # Needs to match the GET method for health checks
```

issue.title: Default S3 compatible provider in metadata writer
issue.body:
Hi Team,

For the provider part, in the [artifact storage URI](https://github.com/kubeflow/pipelines/blob/master/backend/metadata_writer/src/metadata_writer.py#L106-L113) function of metadata writer module, we're checking if the endpoint is Amazon S3 compatible by [matching the endpoint](https://github.com/kubeflow/pipelines/blob/master/backend/metadata_writer/src/metadata_writer.py#L98) with `'^.*s3.*amazonaws.com.*$'`. If it matches we return the provider as S3 else the default is minio.

I think the default should be S3 not minio as there are many S3-compatible object store providers whose endpoint might not match with `'^.*s3.*amazonaws.com.*$'` regex.

cc @johnugeorge
